The article discusses the historic milestone of open government in the Obama administration. It highlights the release of government openness plans by all cabinet agencies, which aim to dismantle barriers and increase transparency, citizen participation, and collaboration. Each agency has identified a main program that showcases innovation and openness. Some examples include the Community Health Data Initiative by the Department of Health and Human Services, the Open Energy Information platform by the Department of Energy, the Innovation Initiative by the Department of Veterans Affairs, and the Homelessness Prevention Resources Initiative by the Department of Housing and Urban Development. The article also mentions new guidelines on the use of social media and the Paperwork Reduction Act to improve transparency in the regulatory process. The White House Open Government Initiative and the Federal Chief Technology Officer have worked with the public to gather input and formulate measures to achieve a more transparent and participatory government.